value: @lizzkats, I want to work with you because you have the foundation of a strong leader in tech, you're also open to new ideas and comfortable asking for help when you need to. This makes our learning more efficient and I would want to work with you more if you pushed your level of understanding on a few technical areas to a point where you feel more comfortable teaching others. Currently, it seems that you're learning topics to complete a task. For example, if you're learning a new topic. I would copy the code in a new text editor and make changes. Have a clear idea of the outcome you would expect, then console.log to see if you are right. I think tactics like this will really help your understanding and might help you share your immense knowledge with others.

You gave me space (and a reasonable, agreed-upon time limit) to try to figure out solutions while honoring your own needs. I really appreciated that. I would work with you again anytime though I would encourage you to try to bring up outside time commitments on the first day of future projects (it did not affect me in any way, but it may affect future partners).

"{{subject}}, I want to work with you because... and I would want to work with you more if..."
subject: drA
value:
I would like to work with you again because I learned a lot from you this week, both technically and regarding team play. Your focus and intense dedication are something that I wish everyone had more of! You helped us roll through all the unexpected curveballs, especially regarding Git and the DB challenges. 

Thanks for being patient with my impatience. I'm thankful that you're in House Kraken and that your well-rounded and impressive skills include a great eye and flow with HTML, CSS, and jQuery.

I would want to work with you more if you would pause more to check in with your teammate(s). Please communicate any worries about the project more directly and especially when you feel as if you want to take over unfinished aspects and anything that hasn't gone as planned.

Tension had built up toward the end of the week and we didn't communicate as well as we could have. HOWEVER, there was Friday and I really appreciated our trio's conversation. 

Thanks for being open to feedback and providing good feedback in return. I appreciated that we had a mature conversation about everything that went on during the week. I'll gladly work with you again, especially on something that's more front-end based as I know that we could learn more from each other and make all the things look beautiful.

subject: breyana
value:
In this feedback, I am mindfully restricting myself from mentioning all of the points where I could improve and how I might have supported the team more effectively - if I gave the areas for improvement in this retro a title it would be "How To Be Perfect When Your Teammate Is Not." Overall, I am really proud of the team's progress and process because we spent time accomplishing our goals and learning about things that continued to stump more experienced players. I also like our end product.

Okay, here goes:

I want to work with you because you are close to your code, aware of your intentions for what you have written and able to explain it clearly. You were also driven to contribute even when you weren't feeling well. In the beginning I felt like I wanted to spend more time figuring things out together before asking for outside help, but when it was time to switch from React, you were open. I also noticed that you were more open to diving in towards the end of the week, which I appreciated. When I pushed to spend a little more time on event listeners, you went with it.

I come from a more object-oriented coding background, so I am adapting to functional programming as well as Javascript. I hope I will have a better grasp on functional programming if/when we work together again. I'd also be curious to see what either of us would learn if we took considered and/or applied object-oriented programming to a coding project. Regarding team play, I felt like you showed strong leadership and problem-solving. I think you absorbed my ideas better when I wrote them out in pseudo-code or when someone else was there to help with communication. I could also tell that you were making an effort to be patient and present even when it was challenging for you. Our minds work in similar ways when approaching logic, so I look forward to working together when we both have more experience supporting stuck teammates and coding.

value: I would very much enjoy working with you again. You are at ease with everything, and yet you still keep gears towards the project. You have a zen-like quality of balance between the tensions of fun and engagement; You push both forwards at the same time, I want to learn to mimic you on this. I very much enjoyed your thought process. You admit your weaknesses, and you work around them. You don't complain about them, nor do you needlessly bash your head on your weaknesses trying to improve at something you may just not have an innate ability to do.. instead you take the wiser route, working around. Specifically, you recognize that you learn best by diving into code, instead of reading material. Instead of taking some people's advice and just "forcing" yourself to read, which you could get better at slowly, you learn by doing what you DO know how to do. Coding. If the end result is the same (learning the concept) then you're taking the correct approach. Some people will tell you that you need to learn to read documents. Sure, do it if you have to. But don't lose your wisdom to know when you get more benefit from doing it your way. I myself learned a lot by watching how you code Things. Finally, I absolutely loved how you allowed me to do my own thing, and then we paired later, after I understood the content better. You seem to have a perfect balance on "teaching" *as* you code, without slowing down as Shareef says.

question:
Give feedback to your teammate by completing the following sentence:

"{{subject}}, I want to work with you because... and I would want to work with you more if..."
subject: Elleyes
value:
You did a great job of setting aside time each day to check in on how everyone was feeling, and to take a few moments to talk about what was real for them, outside of the project. This made me feel more connected on a personal level. You were good at stepping into a leadership role when initiating 30 minute talks at the beginning and end of the day.
I wish we had been able to really do some paired learning together, I think there is value in your methods and I would have liked to learn from them. As we discussed on Thursday, it seems that there was confusion when you had said that you wanted to take the role of a project manager for the week, and then proceeded to draw out a schedule for us. I assumed this meant that you had planned to keep us on task with our agreed upon methods (solo work Monday and Tuesday, pair work Wednesday and Thursday). I'm disappointed that we did not pair up on Wednesday or Thursday as we had agreed upon on Monday, and I think this is partially due to a miscommunication in what "project managing" meant, and partially due to a resistance to do paired work altogether.  
I think there is a lot to be gained from learning how to solve problems as a team, it's one of the reasons I joined LG versus another program. The 30 minute session we had Thursday before you had to leave was not enough to get engaged or to reach flow. I felt very alone in figuring out each problem, and I felt left behind. You are weeks ahead of me and I was looking forward to working with you and learning from you.
I also found it difficult to give you feedback. When I brought up our lack of pairing on Thursday, it was met with resistance and blame shifting. This made it difficult to be vulnerable about my needs and it made it hard to focus on finding a solution (like discussing how we would pair, and what we would work on). I would like to work with you again if I knew that our agreed upon process would be honored, that we would co-learn together, and that my concerns were met with a receptive attitude.

subject: anasauce
value:
@Anasauce,
Working with you, I can see you understand javascript well enough to put things together.

Here are a few points of controversy that I had in our interactions this week:
1. At the start of our project, you mentioned you knew you needed to work on being able to explain your code, although when I was asking you for explanation, I sensed a level of frustration that was matched with me being left confused on what the code actually meant.
2. There were also times when I had some clear ideas on what the problem might be, based on javascript syntax and/or error content, and my ideas were negated until you were out of ideas and then willing to try what I was saying.
3. When you ask someone to drive, you should allow them to drive, instead of wanting to take control of the keyboard every few minutes. I found this to be frustrating on my part, stemming from what seemed to  be a lack of patience. It seemed to contradict your pet peeve of someone taking control of the keyboard without asking.

The things previously listed caused me to back off from interaction at times, not out of fear, but for sake of progression in both our ZPDs. I felt there was more of a benefit of us learning more about the code  than to argue about the code. This way we could at least be able to discuss the code and/or questions about the code with understanding on both sides. (i.e. answering questions and/or explaining code in a way that either one of us was able to understand)
